                                    >Lugt 5137</ref>.</summary>
                            <seal type="stamp" subtype="monogram">
                                <p>European relief-cut <ref
                                        target="https://image.digitalcollections.manchester.ac.uk/iiif/MS-PERSIAN-00024-000-00005.jp2/1476,253,591,712/full/0/default.jpg"
                                        >monogram with the letter L, surmounted by a coronet within
                                        an oval with internal v-shaped crenellations,
                                        single-ruled</ref>.<lb/>
                                    <dimensions type="seal" unit="mm">
                                        <height>22</height>
                                        <width>19</width>
                                    </dimensions>
                                </p>
                            </seal>
                        </sealDesc>
                    </physDesc>
                    <history>
                        <origin>Probably completed in <origPlace
                                ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7000231" key="place_7000231"
                                >Greater Iran</origPlace> possibly <origDate cert="medium"
                                calendar="#Gregorian" notBefore="1450" notAfter="1500">late 15th
                                century CE</origDate>. The date of <date calendar="#Hijri-qamari"
                                when="1386-02-19">10 Muḥarram 788 AH (11 Feb. 1386 Julian)</date>,
                            which appears in the colophon, is for the completion of this work by the
                            author but not for this manuscript.</origin>
                        <provenance>
                            <p>While the circumstances under which this manuscript arrived in Europe
                                remain unclear, a member of the French Lamoignon family acquired it
                                for the <orgName ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/148184022"
                                    key="person_148184022">Bibliotheca Lamoniana</orgName>, probably
                                sometime in the <date cert="high" notBefore="1675" notAfter="1794"
                                    >eighteenth century</date>. Four monogrammed seal impressions
                                appear in the volume, most likely added in a hurried fashion on
                                behalf of the last member of the family, <persName
                                    ref="https://viaf.org/en/viaf/27161049" key="person_27161049"
                                    role="fmo seal">Chrétien-François de Lamoignon
                                    (1735–1789)</persName>, who describes it as <q xml:lang="fr"
                                    >Muur Mustery: Livre en langue Perſienne</q>in his 1770 library
                                catalogue, p. 475.</p></provenance>
                        <provenance><p>After de Lamoignon's death, Parisian antiquarian bookseller
                                    <persName role="bsl fmo" key="person_46858532"
                                    ref="https://viaf.org/en/viaf/46858532">Jean-Gabriel Mérigot
                                    (1738–1818)</persName> acquired the <orgName
                                    ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/148184022" key="person_148184022"
                                    >Bibliotheca Lamoniana</orgName> then published a catalogue in
                                    <date calendar="#Gregorian" when="1791">1791</date>, (for this
                                manuscript see Vol. 2, p. 39, no. 348) then likely sold the volume
                                to French orientalist <persName type="standard"
                                    ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/51695910" key="person_51695910"
                                    role="fmo" change="#role-assignment">Antoine-Isaac Silvestre de
                                    Sacy (1758-1838)</persName>.</p></provenance>
                        <provenance><p>After de Sacy's death, his son <persName role="fmo"
                                    ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/29658127" key="person_29658127">
                                    Samuel Ustazade Silvestre de Sacy (d. 1879)</persName>
                                presumably inherited then sold many of his father's oriental
                                manuscripts through Parisian booksellers <persName role="bsl auc"
                                    ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/75238691" key="person_75238691">Romain
                                    Merlin (1793–1871)</persName> and <persName role="bsl auc"
                                    ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/56958724" key="person_56958724"
                                    >Grangeret de la Grange, (1790-1859)</persName> in <date
                                    calendar="#Gregorian" when="1843">1843</date> (no. 302), where
                                an individual named 'Moore' purchased it.</p></provenance>
                        <provenance><p>Thereafter acquired by scholar <persName type="standard"
                                    role="fmo" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/20108923/"
                                    key="person_20108923">Nathaniel Bland (1803–1865)</persName> for
                                his library at Randalls Park, <placeName
                                    ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7011735"
                                    key="place_7011735">Leatherhead</placeName>.</p></provenance>
                        <provenance>
                            <p>After Bland's death, <placeName
                                    ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7011781"
                                    key="place_7011781">London</placeName> bookseller <persName
                                    role="bsl" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/5679225/"
                                    key="person_5679225">Bernard Quaritch (1819–1899)</persName>
                                sold his oriental manuscripts to <persName role="fmo"
                                    ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/97751058/" key="person_97751058"
                                    >Alexander Lindsay, 25th Earl of Crawford (1812–1880)</persName>
                                in <date calendar="#Gregorian" when="1866-06">June, 1866</date>,
                                paid in two instalments of £450 and £400, and then moved to <orgName
                                    ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/295427552" key="person_295427552"
                                    >Bibliotheca Lindesiana</orgName> at Haigh Hall, <placeName
                                    ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7010384"
                                    key="place_7010384">Wigan</placeName>. </p></provenance>
                        <provenance>Purchased by <persName type="standard" role="dnr"
                                key="person_f6379">Enriqueta Rylands (1843–1908)</persName> in <date
                                calendar="#Gregorian" when="1901">1901</date> from <persName
                                type="standard" role="fmo" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/9985420/"
                                key="person_9985420">James Ludovic Lindsay, 26th Earl of Crawford
                                (1847–1913)</persName>. </provenance>
                        <acquisition>
                            <p>Bequeathed by <persName type="standard" key="person_f6379">Enriqueta
                                    Rylands (1843–1908)</persName> in <date calendar="#Gregorian"
                                    when="1908">1908</date> to the <orgName type="corporation"
                                    role="rps" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/312795145/">John Rylands
                                    Library</orgName>.</p>
                        </acquisition>
                    </history>
